			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">There are two different buses in the NES. The CPU can see only the CPU bus, with RAM at $0000-$07FF, MMIO at $2000-$401F, and ROM at $8000-$FFFF. There is a separate bus connected to the PPU, with pattern tables at $0000-$1FFF, nametables at $2000-$2FFF, and the palette at $3F00-$3F1F. The only way to write to memory on the PPU bus is through the PPU's MMIO ports $2006 and $2007. When you write something to $2007 during vertical blanking or forced blanking, it doesn't actually get stored at $2007 anywhere. The PPU sees it as a request to do the following:<br /><ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Write the value at the current VRAM address, which could be pointing to pattern table memory, nametable memory, or palette memory, depending on how $2006 was set </li><li>Add 1 or 32 to the current VRAM address, depending on the increment setting in $2000 </li></ol></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
